h3. Issue Summary
When allowing users from your @domain to get access to your site, we make sure that your organization will be able to log in to your Atlassian site - even if we disable new users to be granted with product access, at least the users are created there.
Though, if a regular user either share a JIRA issue or Confluence page with someone that is/is not added to the user management, this user is added to the site and granted with product access.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
*Part #1: Make sure to allow users from your domain to have access in your site*
# Go to your *Site Administration > Site Access*;
# Check the second option *Approve the following domains*;
# Add your @domain.com and hit enter;
# Click on *Save Changes*.

*Part #2: Disable new users with product access*
# Go to your *Site Administration > Product Access*;
# Untoggle all the *New users have access to this product* options.

*Part #3: Reproducing the issue*
# Log in with a regular user with no admin or site-admin permissions;
# Access either a Confluence page or JIRA issue with this user;
# In the content you accessed, hit the *share* option;
# Type an email address from a user that doesn't have access to the site or have access to the site but with no product access - be sure this email address belongs to the @domain.com you set on *Step #1*;
# Copy the URL;
# On an incognito window, paste the link and log in to the site with the email you shared the content.

h3. Expected Results
You are supposed to fall in a screen asking to request access to that product.

h3. Actual Results
You are able to log in on the site, seeing the content that was shared.

*NOTES*:
* even if the shared content has some permissions/restrictions that prevent the user to see that content, the product access was granted - with your *site-admin* account, access this user profile and you will that.

h3. Workaround
Remove the @domain.com from the *Site Access*, for now.

h3. Current Scenario
When users are facing login issues, they may end up on a dead-end, without know where to ask for help to solve their issue. They may not know our support channels, and how to find them.

h3. Suggested Solution
When users face login issues, a proposed solution would be to bring our help to their direct view, and provide a quick way to reach out to us:
{quote}
 A "help" link that is displayed on an error screen when a user can not log in should NOT take the user to a location where they need to log in to submit a ticket. With an additional option to "click here to send an email to Atlassian support" or provide some other avenue for users to contact you besides hunting around your website hoping to find a way to get in touch.{quote}

h3. Issue Summary
Inconsistent result for *Worked on* result from *People* page https://instancename/jira/people/userAAID/work

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Go to *People* page https://instancename/jira/people/userAAID/work
# Click on *Jira* link from 
 !workdon.png|thumbnail! 
h3. Expected Results
Consistent result 

h3. Actual Results
Inconsistent result from the *JQL* vs *Worked on* page

JQL query
{code}
assignee in (username) OR reporter in (username) OR creator in (username) OR watcher in (username) ORDER BY updated DESC
{code}

It looks like the *Worked on* is using graphql api but when click on *Jira* link, it's using JQL as shown from the browser console
{code}
Request URL: https://instancename.atlassian.net/gateway/api/worklens/api/graphql?q=WorkedOn
{code}
{code}
query WorkedOn($first: Int = 10, $userIds: [ID]!, $cloudIds: [ID], $objectTypes: [ActivityObjectType]) {  myActivities {    workedOn(first: $first, filter: {aaIDs: $userIds, cloudIDs: $cloudIds, objectTypes: $objectTypes}) {      nodes {        id        eventType        timestamp        contributors {          lastAccessedDate          profile {            accountId            name            __typename          }          __typename        }        containers {          name          __typename        }        object {          id          name          url          iconUrl: iconURL          provider: product          cloudId: cloudID          __typename        }        __typename      }      __typename    }    __typename  }}
{code}

h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Issue Summary

According to [the documentation for the https://api.atlassian.com/users/\{account_id}/manage UM REST API endpoint|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/admin/user-management/rest/?_ga=2.184979945.1354938109.1576579054-1080961822.1564054573#api-users-account-id-manage-get], the response should include information about MFA settings for the user:
{quote} 
- *mfa.read*: read the current MFA enrollment state for the user
- *mfa.unenroll*: unenroll the user from MFA
{quote}

However this is not working. Indeed:
 # Calling [https://api.atlassian.com/users/\{account_id}/manage] does not include above properties in the response
 # Calling [https://api.atlassian.com/users/\{account_id}/manage?privileges=mfa.read] (or mfa.unenroll) always returns {{"allowed":true}}, whether you have MFA enabled or not:
{noformat}
curl -H 'Authorization: Bearer <API_KEY>' -H 'Accept: application/json' -X GET https://api.atlassian.com/users/<ACCOUNT_ID>/manage?privileges=mfa.read

{"mfa.read":{"allowed":true}}
{noformat}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Being an Organization administrator, go to admin.atlassian.com and [Create an API KEY|https://confluence.atlassian.com/cloud/create-an-admin-api-key-969537932.html]
 # Use the api key to authorize a REST API call against the endpoint [https://api.atlassian.com/users/\{account_id}/manage] (replace account_id with the account-id of a [managed account|https://confluence.atlassian.com/cloud/managed-accounts-873871203.html])
 
 h3. Expected Results
 
 Among the other properties, also *mfa.read* and *mfa.unenroll* are returned.
 h3. Actual Results
 
 Everything is returned, but *mfa.read* and *mfa.unenroll*

 Also:
 - Calling: [https://api.atlassian.com/users/\{account_id}/manage?privileges=mfa.read] or [https://api.atlassian.com/users/\{account_id}/manage?privileges=mfa.unenroll] always returns {{"allowed":true}} regardless MFA being enabled or not.
{noformat}
curl -H 'Authorization: Bearer sDXXXXXXXXXXXXaa' -H 'Accept: application/json' -X GET https://api.atlassian.com/users/5acbXXXXXXXXXXXXede/manage?privileges=mfa.read,mfa.unenroll

{"mfa.read":{"allowed":true}}
{noformat}

 
 - Calling [https://api.atlassian.com/users/\{account_id}/manage?privileges=mfa.read,mfa.unenroll] returns empty response:
{noformat}
curl -H 'Authorization: Bearer sDXXXXXXXXXXXXaa' -H 'Accept: application/json' -X GET https://api.atlassian.com/users/5acbXXXXXXXXXXXXede/manage?privileges=mfa.read,mfa.unenroll

{}
{noformat}

h3. Workaround

No workaround available at the moment.

h3. Issue Summary

The [Get user management permissions|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/admin/user-management/rest/?_ga=2.223262363.1054603554.1575971654-1080961822.1564054573#api-users-account-id-manage-get] documentation page is missing information about _mfa.read_ and _mfa.unenroll_ query parameters:
{quote}
h5. QUERY PARAMETERS

*privileges*

Array<string>
{quote}
{quote}Valid values: {{profile}}, {{profile.write}}, {{profile.read}}, {{email.set}}, {{email.initiateChange - lifecycle.enablement}}, {{linkedAccounts.read}}, {{apiToken.read}}, {{apiToken.delete}}, {{avatar}}, {{privacy.set}}
{quote}
 

However, the same parameters are mentioned in the "Responses" section:
{quote}_email.set_: set a new value for the user's email address - _email.initiateChange_: initiate an email address change - *_mfa.read_: read the current MFA enrollment state for the user - _mfa.unenroll_: unenroll the user from MFA* ......
{quote}
 

The parameter is there and it is working fine, it should therefore be added to the list of the valid values:
curl -H 'Authorization: Bearer <API_KEY>' -H 'Accept: application/json' -X GET https://api.atlassian.com/users/<ACCOUNT_ID>/manage?privileges=mfa.read

 
{"mfa.read":{"allowed":true}}

h3. Issue Summary

Currently, you can set the visibility of your full name to *Anyone*, and your organization.

The Public name will then be displayed in Atlassian's public forums.

h3. Suggestion

Provide more granular options to the Full name's visibility, such as:
* Organization;
* Atlassian;
* Atlassian Community (authenticated users);
* Anyone (unauthenticated users).
